the right to deny a child admission to school just because a mentally-ill narcissistic parent says &quot;No&quot;. &#10;I speak as a parent who has sent children through public school and home school to the University of California. &#10;Home schooling is very hard work. Meeting the a-g requirements for enrollment to the University of California was difficult when one takes a different path. &#10;Home schooling should always be motivated by the child and *not* the parent. My youngest wanted to go *faster* than K-12 offered - even though we are in a community with excellent public schools. She enrolled in community college at 12 and carried a full-time load at entering freshman level. She's now at UC Berkeley. &#10;As I stated, education is a fundamental right. No state can take this right away. And no person - not even a biological parent - should have the ability to interfere as well. &#10;Any parent who prevents his own child from obtaining an education is a criminal merely seeking to enslave his own child and should be treated accordingly by the state. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1345" language="en" documentId="250" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="alsmithee" date="7/29/2013 7:41 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375119699-157-408" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="250" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="275"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="276" end="408"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="409" end="522"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="523" end="680"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55